{"type":"message","id":"99aefefc","parentId":"6c0c3a03","timestamp":"2026-06-01T06:46:27.834Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The sub-agent that was spawned earlier to trigger the pipeline is probably still running or has completed. Let me just focus on getting the cookies. But the problem is that I'm running on the server, not the user's local machine. `C:\\Users\\yyzypublic` on the server (zt-c600365) is likely the agent's user, and the user might not have logged into DevOps in that browser.\n\nWait, actually the user exported 2 cookies from their Chrome earlier. This means they are probably chatting with me from a different machine (their dev machine), not the server. So extracting from the server's Chrome won't help - the login was on the user's machine.\n\nHmm, let me reconsider. The agent runs on zt-c600365. But earlier, I was able to run Unity and access files at `E:\\Solo\\nightoffullmoon`. The user's workspace is on this machine. So maybe this IS the user's dev machine. If they logged into DevOps in Chrome on this machine, then the session should be in Chrome's user data dir.\n\nBut wait - the user exported cookies manually and pasted them. That suggests they're at a machine with Chrome and manually extracted cookies. If this is the same machine, the cookies should already be in Chrome.\n\nLet me just run the script and see what happens. If it works, great. If not, I need to ask the user to export more cookies.\n\nActually, let me think about the user's workflow more carefully. They pasted 2 raw cookie JSON objects. They might have used a Chrome extension like \"EditThisCookie\" or \"Cookie Editor\" to export those. If we're on the same machine, using Playwright with Chrome user data should work.\n\nLet me run it.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_xbsx2cOIYXv3xV0VW0TI7982","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\.openclaw\\workspace; node scripts/devops