{"type":"message","id":"9787aece","parentId":"2b663569","timestamp":"2026-06-01T07:06:35.514Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The owner sent the same 2 cookies again. They don't have the Keycloak session cookies. Perhaps the extension they're using only shows these 2 cookies for .devcloud.ztgame.com, and the Keycloak cookies are on a different domain.\n\nLet me look at the domains more carefully:\n- `.devcloud.ztgame.com` - this is where the devops cookies live\n- `keycloak.devcloud.ztgame.com` - this is where the Keycloak session cookies would be\n\nWait, actually `keycloak.devcloud.ztgame.com` is a subdomain of `devcloud.ztgame.com` but with a different subdomain. Chrome stores cookies per domain, so cookies set by `keycloak.devcloud.ztgame.com` would be under that specific subdomain, not `.devcloud.ztgame.com`.\n\nThe user needs to also check for cookies specifically from `keycloak.devcloud.ztgame.com`. But also, since they said \"登录了\" - maybe they logged in on Chrome but the session cookie is `httpOnly` and the extension can't see it.\n\nLet me try a different approach. Maybe I should try to automate this differently. Let me look at what cookies the Keycloak SSO sets. Common Keycloak cookies include:\n- `KEYCLOAK_SESSION`\n- `KEYCLOAK_IDENTITY`\n- `AUTH_SESSION_ID`\n\nThese would be set by `keycloak.devcloud.ztgame.com`.\n\nActually, the user just said \"登录了\" - maybe I should interpret this as them having logged in through the Playwright browser that was previously open. Let me check if the headed browser from the `devops_qrcode_login.mjs` script might still be running...\n\nActually no, I killed that process earlier.\n\nLet me think about what approach would work:\n1. The user doesn't seem to have an extension that shows all cookies for keycloak.devcloud.ztgame.com\n2. The previous Playwright headed approach failed because I couldn't show the QR code to the user\n3. Chrome is running so I can't launch another instance with the same profile\n\nWait - maybe I can try a different Playwright approach. Instead of launching a new Chrome instance, I can connect to the already-running Chrome instance using the `--remote-debugging-port` feature.\n\nLet me check if the existing Chrome was launched with a debugging port. Actually, I can try to find the remote debugging port or launch Chrome with a new flag.\n\nActually, a simpler idea: I can have the user:\n1. Open Chrome's DevTools (F12)\n2. Go to Application tab → Cookies\n3. Look for all cookies under `devcloud.ztgame.com` AND `keycloak.devcloud.ztgame.com`\n4. Copy them\n\nOr alternatively, I can try launching Chrome with `--remote-debugging-port=9222` to connect Playwright to the existing user data directory.\n\nActually, the simplest approach: let me just try to connect to the already-running Chrome via CDP (Chrome DevTools Protocol). But Chrome doesn't expose CDP by default without `--remote-debugging-port`.\n\nHmm, let me try yet another approach. Let me check if there's a Chrome extension installed that can export cookies, or I can create a script that uses the already-running Chrome.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-examine this problem. The user logged into DevOps in Chrome. The devops_token is a JWT that likely just needs cookies from `.devcloud.ztgame.com` and `keycloak.devcloud.ztgame.com`.\n\nLet me look at what cookies might exist. From the earlier keepalive, there were 25 cookies. When I saved 22 cookies from the Playwright session, it had enough cookies to work (though that session ended up at the login screen because the Feishu auth wasn't complete).\n\nLet me try another approach - write a script that starts a headed Playwright with a NEW temporary user data directory (not the existing Chrome profile), navigates to DevOps, waits for the user to log in manually (with 2 minute timeout), and then saves the cookies.\n\nThe script would:\n1. Create a temp user data directory\n2. Launch Playwright with it (headless: false)\n3. Navigate to DevOps\n4. Show the login page\n5. Wait for the user to manually log in (by viewing the window on the server)\n6. Save cookies after login\n\nBut the user can't see the server's screen...\n\nOK, I think the real issue is that the 2 cookies the user keeps sending are the only ones visible in their cookie extension for `.devcloud.ztgame.com`. The Keycloak session cookies are set by `keycloak.devcloud.ztgame.com` which is a different domain.\n\nLet me just ask the user to also export cookies for `keycloak.devcloud.ztgame.com`.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"主人，这些还是刚才那 2 个。DevOps 的登录 session 实际上保存在 **`keycloak.devcloud.ztgame.com`** 这个域下，麻烦扩展里也查一下这个域的 Cookie，有的话一起导出来给我🙏"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":7461,"output":1089,"cacheRead":39552,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":48102,"cost":{"input":0.00104454,"output":0.00030492000000000003,"cacheRead":0.001107456,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.002456916}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1780297584931,"responseId":"390afb7d-6159-400e-9c88-5c5b090bb529"}}
